snippet.textDisplay: The other two versions got a nose job along the way but the Silhouette kept its original shape. The different horspowers over the  years were from different engines, although the original 3.1 V6 later got multipoint fuel injection and fifty more horsepower. And quality was not any worse than a typical American or GM car in the 90's. And the reason you don't see them is because they didn't sell in huge numbers and that was a long time ago. The bodies didn't rust because they are all plastic. But of course everything underneath could rust. I had an original 1990 Pontiac version and there was no warning sticker on the front door frame. And I never came close to bonking my head on it.  Obviously all the seat backs fold flat so for carrying a lot of big stuff like a flat pack from Ikea or Home Depot you didn' have to pull the seats out. Average cars were less powerful then, but these are significantly smaller in every dimension than a current minivan and a whole lot lighter.

snippet.textDisplay: We bought a new Silhouette with the 3100 V6 engine when our 2 kids were 3 and 4.  It was a very good van for us and lasted until our boys were in their mid 20's.  This was my wife's primary vehicle and all of our boys friends wanted rides in it because they thought it looked like a Star Trek shuttle craft and not a dust buster.  There were plenty of other cars and vans that were really ugly like the jelly bean Toyota van, cheese wedge Prius, Aztec van and so many modern day cars - the Silhouette was not weird for its day in my opinion and it was very comfortable.  Through the years little things broke as they do on all cars and eventually  this van became mine to use for hauling stuff.  I loaned it to one of the boys one day to pick up something large and it was returned with a blown engine - he still has a lead foot even now.  My wife cried when it was towed away - wish I still had it.
